Definition of the basic model

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dS}{dt} &=- \beta_w I_wS - \beta_z I_z S + \gamma I_z + \gamma(1 - \varepsilon)I_w + \gamma ` \varepsilon I_w \\ \frac{dI_w}{dt} &=\beta_w I_wS + (1-\varepsilon)\beta_wI_wI_z - \gamma(1 - \varepsilon)I_w - \gamma ` \varepsilon I_w - \varepsilon\beta_zI_zI_w - \rho\varepsilon I_w \\ \frac{dI_z}{dt} &=\beta_z I_zS + \varepsilon\beta_zI_zI_w + \rho\varepsilon I_w - \gamma I_z - (1-\varepsilon)\beta_wI_wI_z \\ \end{aligned} \]

State variables

Name of state variable Description
\(S\) proportion of population that is susceptible
\(I_w\) proportion of population that is infected with sensitive strain
\(I_z\) proportion of population that is infected with resistant strain

Parameters

Name of Parameter Description Default value
\(\beta_w\) transmission rate of sensitive strain 0.40
\(\beta_z\) transmission rate of resistant strain 0.15
\(\varepsilon\) proportion of infected people treated with antibiotics, supposedly strongly correlated to \(AMU\) 0.10
\(\gamma\) innate recovery rate (relative to \(I_z\) generally and to \(I_w\) (not treated with antibiotics) 0.01
\(\gamma '\) recovery rate of \(I_w\) when treated with antibiotics 0.1
\(\rho\) proportion of treatment failures in \(I_w\) (comprehensing de novo mutations, outcompetition of major sensitive strain by minor resistant one and horizontal transfer) 0.05

Additional variables

Synthetic variables

Name of synthetic variable Description Formula
\(P\) ratio of resistant prevalence \(P = \frac{I_z}{I_z+I_w}\)
\(I\) ratio of resistant incidence \(I = \frac{new I_z}{newI_z+newI_w}\)

Antimicrobial consumption

Name of variable Description Formula
\(C\) drug concentration (per patient per unit of time)
\(AMU\) antimicrobial usage \(AMU = \varepsilon*C*t\)
\(Q\) drug quantity per patient \(Q=C*t\)
\(\Gamma\) equivalent drug quantity used in agriculture
\(E\) drug quantity (in absolute values) \(E=\varepsilon*Q*(I_w+a*I_z)+\Gamma\)

Derivatives

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dP}{dt} &= P(1-q)\beta_z - P(1-q)[(1-P)\beta_w + P\beta_z] - P(1-P)[\gamma-\left( \gamma(1-\varepsilon)+\gamma'\varepsilon\right)]+(1-P)[-Pq\left((1-\varepsilon)\beta_w-\varepsilon\beta_z\right)+\rho\varepsilon] \\ &= -P(1-q)(1-P)(\beta_w-\beta_z) - P(1-P)[\gamma-\left( \gamma(1-\varepsilon)+\gamma'\varepsilon\right)]+(1-P)[-Pq\left((1-\varepsilon)\beta_w-\varepsilon\beta_z\right)+\rho\varepsilon] \\ \\ \frac{dq}{dt} &= q[(1-q)\left((1-P)\beta_w+P\beta_z)\right) - \gamma - \varepsilon (1-P)(\gamma'-\gamma) ] \end{aligned} \]

Where: \[ \begin{aligned} q=I_z+I_w \\ P=\frac{I_z}{I_z+I_w} \end{aligned} \]

Steady state exploration

Steady states when varying \(\varepsilon\)

According to our model, the proportions of different populations change for the range of \(\varepsilon\) (proportion of treated patients) between 0 and 20%. \(I_w\) decreases linearly with the increase of \(\varepsilon\). For now on, the behavior of our model will be analyzed for this span of \(\varepsilon\) (!! relevance??).

Steady states when varying \(\rho\)

Based on literature, the proportion of treatment failures is between 4 and 8% (add a quote) for tuberculosis. It has a significant impact on the proportion of \(I_w\) and \(I_z\). When it increases, the prevalence of \(I_z\) increases at the expense of \(I_w\), while the global burden of the disease decreases. Interestingly, when there is no treatment failure, there is no stable coexistence of sensitive and resistant strains in our model.

Steady state E when varying \(\varepsilon\)

We consider Quantity of antibiotics as being the burden of infection multiplied by the proportion of treated patients. In fact, usage of ATB in patients infected with resistant strains does not have any impact on patient’s recovery in our model. Though, here we consider that the ATB are consumed in this subpopulation as well and at the same rate, which may be due to poor or late resistance detection in hospitals or to self-medication in population.

Therefore in this model, \(E = (I_w +I_z)*\varepsilon\).

The following plot represents the E in function of \(\varepsilon\).

The first part of the graph results from a multiplication of a decreasing linear function (\(I_w + I_z\)) and an increasing linear function (\(\varepsilon\)). For extreme values of \(\varepsilon\), there is a linear relation between \(E\) and \(\varepsilon\) as \(I_w + I_z\) reaches stability.

This means that at steady states, with nearly the same quantity of antibiotics \(E\) (0.05 and 0.06) nearly a double proportion of patients can be treated (10% and 17%).

Steady state net flow in the model

The steady state flows from one population to another are followed for \(\varepsilon\) varying between 0 and 20%.

Flow Comparison Flow
\(S\) to \(I_w\) > \(I_w\) to \(S\)
\(I_w\) to \(I_z\) > \(I_z\) to \(I_w\)
\(S\) to \(I_z\) < \(I_z\) to \(S\)

Steady state resistance ratio P and burden of resistance

Here, the P corresponds to the ratio of resistant prevalence at steady-states. Usually, it is used in the studies of tuberculosis (WHO 2002). Its exponential growth is due to the interplay of increasing \(I_z\) and decreasing \(I_w\).

P, the ratio of resistant prevalence, as a function of E shows an exponential growth with saturation, which is due to :

  1. interplay of increasing \(I_z\) and decreasing \(I_w\) with increasing \(\varepsilon\)
  2. saturation part of the curve of Q=f(\(\varepsilon\)) ([0.050, 0.06] of \(E\) corresponds to [10%,17%] of \(\varepsilon\))

Here, the burden of infection corresponds to the total proportion of infected people. It decreases linearly as the \(\varepsilon\) increases, due to the decrease of \(I_w\) that is faster than the increase of \(I_z\).

Finally, when plotting the BOI in function of E, decreasing tendency is preserved. Before reaching a stability, there is a fastening decrease of BOI, which is once again due to the saturation tendancy in \(E\)=f(\(\varepsilon\)).

Steady state incidence

Though the burden of infection decreases linearly with the use of antibiotics, the global incidence evolves in a more complex way. There is a peak for incidence when app. 7% of the patients are treated.

The increase of global incidence for lower values of \(\varepsilon\), cannot be solely explained by the emergence of resistance and its spread : the incidence of sensitive infections increases until 5% \(\varepsilon\). In fact, though the proportion of sensitive cases decreases very fast with \(\varepsilon\) in comparison to the speed of increase of susceptible population, their product increases until app. 9% \(\varepsilon\) and remains at equal or higher values of the situation without \(\varepsilon\) until app. 11% of \(\varepsilon\). The increasing spread of resistant infections explains then the delayed peak of global incidence in comparison with the sensitive one.

The global incidence then decreases to its value without antibiotic use at 14% \(\varepsilon\).

The situation where resistance emerges in a treated patient, comprehending a horizontal tranfer of AMR, \(de\) \(novo\) mutations and minor resistant population outcompeting its sensitive fellows, is called secondary resistance.

This resistance is represented in our model as a flow from \(I_w\) to \(I_z\) depending on the \(\varepsilon\) and probability of acquiring resistance when treated. As we can see, it reaches a peak for 10% \(\varepsilon\). For higher values of \(\varepsilon\), the deterioration of \(I_w\) population makes the secondary resistance plummet.

When relating I and Q, the proportion of resistant cases among new cases increases very steeply at higher values (0.050 ti 0.060) of E. This is once again due to:

  1. exponential increase in P=f(\(\varepsilon\))
  2. relative steadiness in E=f(\(\varepsilon\)) for higher values of \(\varepsilon\) (10 - 17%)

Average duration of sensitive infection (without resistant dynamics)

In fact, as the \(\varepsilon\) varies, so does the average or expected duration of sensitive infection. Increasing \(\varepsilon\) will have for an effect more rapid recovery of sensitive cases. Here, we represent the average duration as a function of \(\varepsilon\) following this formula :

\[Duration = \frac {1}{((1-\varepsilon)*\gamma + \varepsilon*\gamma')}\]

Dynamics exploitation

In this part, we analyse the dynamics in our model. At time \(t=0\), the steady state for \(\varepsilon=10%\) was reached. Afterwards, the \(\varepsilon\) changes to values between 0% and 20%.

Dynamics of P after a change in \(\varepsilon\)

Here, P corresponds to the ratio of resistant prevalence and burden of infection. As the study of its dynamics show, it changes following \(\varepsilon\).

Dynamics of Incidence

We have seen that at steady state the global incidence increases in the interval of 0% to 7% \(\varepsilon\). This means that paradoxically, there are more new infections with higher level of \(\varepsilon\).

Here, we see that in short-term dynamics, the incidence depends strongly on \(\varepsilon\) : when \(\varepsilon\) decreases the global incidence increases for each value of \(\varepsilon\).

There is therefore a transient period, that follows a decrease in \(\varepsilon\), during which the incidence is higher not only than at the prior state but than at equilibrium as well.

DESCRIPTION OF HONEY-MOON PERIOD

On following pages, we will study the cause of this anti-honeymoon period, during which the incidence is strikingly higher than at equilibrium or at the state prior to \(\varepsilon\) reduction.

It is indeed the increase in the incidence of sensitive cases that seems to be responsible for the anti-honeymoon period after an abrupt reduction of \(\varepsilon\).

The susceptible incidence depends on mass product of \(I_w\) and \(S\).

We consider now a simpler model with only \(I_w\) and \(S\) populations, related with the same relationships as in our model. Do these short-term peaks in \(I_w\) incidence appear as well? If it is so, the anti-honeymoon period is due only to the interplay between \(I_w\) and \(S\) when the \(\varepsilon\) is suddenly decreased. The second possibility is that the transient anti-honeymoon period is due to the interplay between \(I_w\) and \(I_z\).

Anti-honeymoon period does not appear in a simpler model and thus this phenomenon emerges due to the presence of \(I_z\).

As the sensitive incidence, and thus the anti-honeymoon period, are directly dependent on the mass-product of \(I_w\) and \(S\), a change in flow between \(I_z\) and \(I_w\) may have a direct impact on the mass product. In particular, the secondary resistance may be the cause of the short-term peaks as the variation of \(\varepsilon\) has a huge and immediate impact on its strength : the decrease of \(\varepsilon\) would decrease this flow and we would see a fast accumulation in \(I_w\) population at the cost of \(I_z\).

Concurrently to the presence of short-term peaks, the \(I_w\) to \(I_z\) flow, corresponding to the spread of resistance in infected cases, plummets. In fact, the decrease of \(\varepsilon\) has an immediate effect on this flow. Meanwhile the impact on the loss of resistance (\(I_z\) to \(I_w\) flow) is slower : it reaches the minimum value by the 150th step.

Finally, dynamics in recovery of infected cases may contribute as well to the anti-honeymoon period : as the \(\varepsilon\) is suddenly decreased, the expectancy of duration spent in \(I_w\) population should increase. This would then transiently promote the accumulation of sensitive cases and therefore the possibility of transmission.

As we can see, the recovery dynamics of sensitive cases after a sudden decrease of \(\varepsilon\) is in accordance with our hypothesis and contribute to the anti-honeymoon effect.

The anti-honeymoon effect, following an abrupt drop in \(\varepsilon\), is a consequence of several phenomena:

  1. The flow from \(I_w\) to \(I_z\) is suddenly cut, while the flow in opposite direction slows down progressively, resulting in a redistribution of infected cases.
  2. The average duration of sensitive infection becomes longer, resulting in accumulation of sensitive cases.
  3. As a result of the accumulation of sensitive cases, the mass product of \(S\) and \(I_w\) increases. In consequence, the \(S\) is transiently drawn by \(I_w\).

Finally, we represent here the net flows between the three subpopulations after a change in \(\varepsilon\):

We can notice that \(I_w\) to \(S\) and \(I_w\) and \(I_z\) net flows are discontinuous because some of their components (\(I_w\) to \(S\), \(I_w\) to \(I_z\) and \(I_z\) to \(I_w\) flows) depend directly on \(\varepsilon\) changing abruptly at t=0. On the otherhand \(I_z\) to \(S\) net flow is continuous because each of its components is independent on \(\varepsilon\).

Inhibition of certain functions in our model

Inhibition of interhost competition

To inhibit the interhost competition in our model, \(\beta_z\) takes the value of \(0.4\) that is to say becomes equal to \(\beta_w\). The intrahost competition remains, although it depends on \(\beta_z\) \(via\) the probability of superinfection.

The steady state values of state variables are the following:

We observe thus coexistence of the strains for values of \(\varepsilon\) between approximately 0 and 15%. When \(I_z\) is fixed, it has the same value as \(I_z\) prevalence during prebiotic era.

Interestingly, when no ATB is used, resistant strain does not coexist with the sensitive one due to indirect cost linked to co-infections. Although no direct cost of resistance is included in this particular model, when resistant cases are reinfected with sensitive strains, the sensitive strain prevails.

Paradoxically the prevalence has the lowest value for \(\varepsilon\) of 10% due to indirect competition. The incidence is highest at the same time as the turnover of sensitive cases is highest (we observe a peak of \(I_w\) and \(S\) mass product). It returns to pre-antibiotic era as \(I_z\) becomes fixed.

As there is no cost of resistance, the interplay between resistant and sensitive strain will depend solely on \(\varepsilon\) and \(\rho\). As \(\varepsilon\), that corresponds to the \(\varepsilon\) here, increases, a higher turnover of sensitive cases occurs, while the flow from \(I_w\) to \(I_z\) increases at the expense of \(I_z\) to \(I_w\) flow.

Interestingly but not surprisingly, the global flows in our model are inversed in comparison with a model including cost of resistance. This is due to the fact that \(I_z\) spreads as easily as \(I_w\). At the same time, patients infected with \(I_w\) do recover more easily than those infected with \(I_z\) as \(\varepsilon\) increases. Therefore there is a stronger flow from \(I_w\) to \(S\) than from \(I_z\), when the populations are equal.

In comparison with the full model, the primary resistance becomes predominant over the secondary one for lower values of \(\varepsilon\), as the resistant bacteria are better transmitted (10% vs 13%). For most diseases, the secondary resistance is estimated to be more prevalent.

In general, when the transmission cost increases, \(i.e.\) the \(\beta_z\) decreases while \(\beta_w\) remains stable, \(I_z\) is fixed and becomes prevalent for higher values of \(\varepsilon\).

Consistant with the above-mentioned findings, when \(\rho=0\), \(i.e.\) there is no treatment failure and therefore no secondary resistance, resistant strain cannot coexist.

Moreover unlike in the situation where the transmission cost does exist, the global burden of infection increases with \(\rho\). This is due to the fact, that the resistant strain has the behaviour of a sensitive one in antibiotics-free environment. Therefore, at values of \(\rho\) incompatible with \(I_w\) coexistence (\(\rho\)>0.15), \(I_z\) gains the same levels as \(I_w\) in antibiotics-free environment (\(I_z\)=0.75; data not shown).

Inhibition of secondary resistance

When only primary resistance is preserved, that is to say \(\rho=0\), we observe that the coexistence is very limited (for \(\varepsilon\) between 0.27 and 0.29).

Although the model was started with an important subpopulation of \(I_z\) (cca 12%), this subpopulation has vanished at steady state, being systematically converted into \(I_w\). The stability of \(I_z\) subpopulation is therefore substantially dependant on the secondary resistance in long term.

Without secondary resistance, the flows between \(I_w\) and \(I_z\) reach equilibria when \(\beta_w*(1-\varepsilon)=\beta_z*\varepsilon\), that is to say when \(\varepsilon=0.73\). The emergence of stable state is therefore rather linked to the upraise of \(S\) values due to enhanced treatment than to the inversion of flows between \(I_z\) and \(I_w\).

Inhibition of primary resistance

Here, the primary resistance is omitted, \(i.e.\) \(\beta_z=0\) and the resistant strains cannot be transmitted.

Although the transmission of resistant strains is omitted and therefore the pool of resistant cases is fully dependant on treatment failures, the coexistence is observed for \(\varepsilon\) < 25% at steady states. Not surprisingly, the resistant cases vanish at the same time as sensitive ones do.

In comparison with a simple model in which only susceptible population and sensitive strains are present, the incidence is smaller for the same \(\varepsilon\). This is due to the treatment failures : in fact, the \(I_z\) will represent here a dead-end for the pathogen that cannot be transmitted.

Study of hysteresis

The study of hysteresis allows to know whether the same stable states can be reached while increasing proportion of treated patients from a low state (\(\varepsilon=0.00\)) or decreasing it from a high state (\(\varepsilon=0.18\)). We opt to consider only the stable states in a relatively short interval of \(\varepsilon\) ([0, 0.18]) so to prevent \(I_w\) from reaching irrescuable 0 (there is no possibility to re-establish \(I_w\) population in our model).

Once the \(\varepsilon\) stabilizes over 0.18, there is a point of no return, not allowing the sensitive bacteria to re-establish. This is due to the fact, that in our model there is no possibility of reversion of resistant mutants which seems to be realistic considering today’s research (changing genetic background and eventual compensatory mutations will make reversion highly unlikely due to accumulation of compensatory mutations).

The back and forth pathways being the same, we can say that there is no hysteresis in our model. Therefore, theoretically resistant cases can be diminished by reduced use of antibiotics. The question now is whether the changing \(\varepsilon\) has the same effect within the same timespan. This brings us to the study of inertia.

Study of inertia

Varying the speed of change of \(\varepsilon\)

Linear variations

In this part, we vary rate at which the proportion of patients varies, still considering that the proportion of patients is directly linked to the \(AMU\). At first, we start from \(\varepsilon\)=0 and increase its value up to 1.

As the rate of change increases, the proportion of \(I_z\) is more distant from its steady state value. The rate of change of \(\varepsilon\) can thus have a severe impact on the detected resistance level. Presuming that all hospitals are in equilibrium can be a rough simplification.

Delay in reaching equilibrium due to rapid increase of \(\varepsilon\) can be observed for the P (defined as the ratio between \(I_z\) and burden of infection) as well.

Sinusoidal variations

Another method of grasping the inertia of a model, consists in varying \(\varepsilon\) periodically. \(\varepsilon\) is here a sine function with a certain pulsation :

\[ \varepsilon=A*sin(\omega*t)+B \\ \] Where \[ A=B=(max \varepsilon - min\varepsilon)/2 \] In order to prevent effects of \(I_w\) extinction due to high \(\varepsilon\), we opted here for 0.00 as the minimum value of \(\varepsilon\) and 0.18 as its maximum value.

The \(\varepsilon\) varies as follows for different values of pulsation \(\omega\) (higher pulsations mean faster change in time) :

We compare the steady state values of \(I_z\) and P to their values while \(\varepsilon\) varies periodically with different pulsations:

The smaller the pulsations are, and therefore the slower the variation of \(\varepsilon\) is, the more the corresponding curve approaches the steady-state curve.

The question is now whether the same times are required for reaching equilibrium (TREs) while increasing or decreasing \(\varepsilon\).

Time to reach equilibrium while increasing or decreasing \(\varepsilon\)

Comparing TREs for the same start value of \(\varepsilon\)

The idea is to compare the number of steps that are required for reaching a steady state while either increasing or decreasing the value of \(\varepsilon\).

The model starts at a steady state for a given value of \(\varepsilon\). Then the \(\varepsilon\) is increased or decreased by certain \(\delta\) and the time required for reaching equilibrium (TRE), represented by a value of convergience criterion (here \(c\)=0.000001). The output is the following comparison of TREs for each starting value of \(\varepsilon\):

For higher values of \(\varepsilon\), when the proportion of treated patients changes, it takes longer time to reach the steady states. The TREs are longer when \(\varepsilon\) is increased and the difference between TREs related to increasing and to decreasing \(\varepsilon\), increases with initial value of \(\varepsilon\).

We consider here only the interval of \(\varepsilon\) where both lineages coexist at considerable values, \(i.e.\) \(I_w\) does not reach an irrescuable 0.

Here, the plot represents the time lapse between reaching equilibrium while decreasing and increasing \(\varepsilon\), either with a large or small \(\delta\) (0.01 and 0.001). For each value of \(\delta\), the time lapse is strictly positive and increases exponentially with the initial value of \(\varepsilon\). Therefore, in general the steady states are reached with a bigger delay when the proportion of treated patients is increased than when it is decreased by the same value.

Interestingly, the difference between TREs is the same although the value of \(\delta\) differs.

We can compare the differences obtained with different values of \(\delta\varepsilon\) (0.01 and 0.001) while using the same metrics such as \(\frac{\delta t}{\delta \varepsilon}\) :

Presumably, when considering the same metrics, the difference between TREs is \(circa\) ten times lower when \(\delta\) is bigger.

Detailing \(AMU\)

Definitions, understanding \(DDD\)

In the previous parts, the \(AMU\) in the model was assimilated to the proportion of treated patients. In reality, the \(AMU\) is reported as defined daily doses (\(DDD\)) per patient/occupied bed per day. Therefore it is a combination of the treatment duration, concentration of daily doses and the number or proportion of patients.

\(DDD/pt/d = \varepsilon*C*t\)

In fact, each of these three components may have an impact on the emergence and spread of resistance.

\(\varepsilon\) intervenes in the recovery of patients, in the secondary resistance and the outcome of intrahost competition.

Concentration intervenes in the mutation rate enabling resistant mutants to appear and in the selection of the mutant. Several recent papers showed that the outcome of mutant selection depends on the relative position of growth rate curves as the function of drug concentration. The difference between the growth rates of a wild type and mutant strains represents selective coefficient. Its value influences the outcome of selection.

Time of treatment can intervene in the mutation selection. It has been shown that short and long drug administrations have the same efficiency in clearance of sensitive pathogen, while with the length of drug administration, the probability of secondary resistance increases.

We neglige other phenomena that may intervene, such as the heterogeneity in the total pathogen population when drug administration is started (and possible success of “hit hard and early” strategy) or the drug consumption in treatment of other diseases.

In the following parts, we will try to implement a more detailed version of the \(AMU\) in the model in order to see the possible impacts of an intrinsic bias linked to the aggregated \(AMU\) reports.

For the sake of clarity, we opt to use at first the Drug quantity per patient (\(Q\)), and consider that it has the same impact as the drug concentration on the outcome of selection. Therefore we have:

\(Q = C*t\)

The drug quantity used per patient will then have an impact on the mutation rate and the selective coefficient.

Model with a detailed version of \(AMU\)

Impact of \(Q\) on mutation rate and selective coefficient

In contrast with our first model, the \(AMU\) is not considered as directly linked to the proportion of treated patients, but as a product of proportion of treated patients (\(\varepsilon\)) and the drug quantity used per patient (\(Q\)).

It has been shown that the mutation rate, here the rate at which resistant mutants appear, grows with increasing \(Q\)/\(C\) (??? source). Here we thus represent the mutation rate as a growing function of \(Q\).

As it has been mentioned above, we consider that the drug quantity has an impact on resistant mutant selection in intrahost dynamics. This impact will depend on the relative position of growth rate curves of mutant and resistant strains.

Here, we will consider two basic scenarios, anticipated by \(Troy Day et al.\) In the first one, the selective coefficient is lowest for the lowest used drug concentration, i.e. the optimal strategy for preventing resistant selection corresponds to the lowest drug concentration (or drug quantity in our simplified model). In the second one it is the oposite : the selective coefficient is lowest for the highest value of drug concentration in the selection window.

The outcome of selection

For each value of \(Q\), the treatment failure rate \(\rho\) will therefore take a different value in the model.

The proportion of treated patients

In order to exploit, to what extent the different combinations of \(\varepsilon\) and \(Q\) can influence the model, the \(AMU\) is fixed at certain value for a given series of simulations. The \(AMU\) is fixed as well as a range of \(Q\), the \(\varepsilon\) is therefore determined for each value of \(Q\):

Impact of possible D-\(\varepsilon\) combinations on steady-states

For a given value of \(AMU\) (0.2), the modeling is performed for both scenarios. Then the steady states are evaluated.

The combination of \(Q\) and \(\varepsilon\) has a big impact on the steady states.

In the first scenario, the maximum reached \(I_z\) at steady state is twice as high as the minimum, while in the second one 5 times.

The impact is even bigger on the reported resistant ratio \(P\) (2.5 fold and 7 fold difference).

Interestingly, the same form of the curve as that of treatment failure rate is observed in both plots, though the maximum are switched to the left (A analyser plus tard). For increased values of \(Q\) the values of \(P\) are lower, which can be linked to the \(\varepsilon\) that is decreasing with increasing drug combination and therefore the susceptible cases are cleansed at lower rate.

Meanwhile, the impact of global burden of disease shows a very little of difference (around 25%) for different combinations:

The burden of the disease increases with the drug quantity which is once again due to the lower recover rate of sensitive cases linked to lower values of \(\varepsilon\).

Varying \(AMU\)

In this part, exactly the same series of simulations are performed and compared for increasing values of \(AMU\).

VA ETRE ANALYSE PROCHAINEMENT.

Model with an impact of E

In this part, we consider that the absolute quantity of consumed antibiotics, E, has an impact on epidemiological dynamics through passive consumption via water and thus passive immunization. The new model is defined by following equations:

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dS}{dt} &=- \beta_w I_wS - \beta_z I_z S + \gamma I_z + \gamma(1 - \epsilon)I_w + \gamma ` \epsilon I_w \\ \frac{dI_w}{dt} &=\beta_w I_wS + (1-\epsilon)\beta_wI_wI_z - \gamma(1 - \epsilon)I_w - \gamma ` \epsilon I_w - \epsilon\beta_zI_zI_w - \rho\epsilon I_w - \rho'I_w \\ \frac{dI_z}{dt} &=\beta_z I_zS + \epsilon\beta_zI_zI_w + \rho\epsilon I_w + \rho'I_w - \gamma I_z - (1-\epsilon)\beta_wI_wI_z \\ \end{aligned} \]

where : \[ \begin{aligned} \beta_w &= \beta_{w_0} - a*E\\ \beta_z &= \beta_{z_0} + b*E\\ \rho' &= c*E\\ \end{aligned} \]

\(\beta_w\) decreases with \(E\) : this relationship is based on these assumptions:

  1. as \(E\) increases, antibiotics spread into environment and people will consume them passively (antibiotics are for exemple diluted in water)
  2. the more people consume antibitics passively, the less probable will be an infectious contact, due to the fact that the body of susceptible person will be passively immunized and less prone to infection

Parameters

Name of Parameter Description Default value
\(a\) rate at which \(\beta_w\) decreases with E 0.01
\(b\) rate at which \(\beta_z\) decreases with E 0.01
\(c\) rate at which \(\rho'\) increases with E 0.001

There are different scenarios considering E that depend on the efficiency of AMR detection :

E expression Scenario
\(E = I_w*Q*\varepsilon\) Ideal AMR detection
\(E = (I_w+I_z)*Q*\varepsilon\) No AMR detection
\(E = I_w*Q*\varepsilon + A\) Environmental use + Ideal AMR detection
\(E = (I_w+I_z)*Q*\varepsilon + A\) Environmental use + No AMR detection
\(E = (I_w+a*I_z)*Q*\varepsilon + A\) General expression

Basic model without detailed AMU

First, we consider that \(Q\)=1, \(i.e.\) we do not detail \(AMU\) as in the previous section. The following steady-states correspond to the “No AMR detection” scenario.

Model with detailed AMU

In this model we consider that \(AMU = Q*\varepsilon\). As in the previous section, we consider that the intrahost selection and mutation rate depend on the quantity of consumed ATB (\(Q\)).

No transmission cost : existing optimal strategy?
